&lt;/ul&gt;</description></item><item><title>[Solution] Python SyntaxError — Invalid Type Comment</title><link>https://errorcode.excellentwiki.com/languages/python/type-comment/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://errorcode.excellentwiki.com/languages/python/type-comment/</guid><description>&lt;h1 id="syntaxerror--invalid-type-comment"&gt;SyntaxError — Invalid Type Comment&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A &lt;code&gt;SyntaxError&lt;/code&gt; with the message &amp;ldquo;invalid type comment&amp;rdquo; is raised when a type comment is malformed. Type comments are special comments that provide type annotations for variables and function signatures, typically used with tools like mypy.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h2 id="description"&gt;Description&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Type comments are a way to add type information to Python code using comments. They follow the format &lt;code&gt;# type: &amp;lt;type&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt; for variables and &lt;code&gt;# type: (&amp;lt;args&amp;gt;) -&amp;gt; &amp;lt;return&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt; for functions. Invalid syntax in these comments causes &lt;code&gt;SyntaxError&lt;/code&gt;. Modern Python prefers inline annotations over type comments.&lt;/p&gt;</description></item></channel></rss>